 the bell on ship to let them see me getting flogged you see. Well anyway I thought to myself well, I'm going to get away from this. So my - this fellow there called Witchie, he come from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1535702\charrsid16398449 Glasgow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5265281\charrsid16398449 
, and he says I'm going to get away Arthur, he says, I can't stick - I can't stick here. Punish us terrible there. Up in the loft - up - up aloft at four o'clock in the morning with weather, you know, bare feet and - then you had to - had to
 do - naughts and splices, bends and bitches, rope - rope pulling, swimming - had to swim - had to swim half a mile with your clothes on in the sea. Well - I says, well I says, there's a starboard watch to go into the field this afternoon and I says I'm g
o
ing to - I'm going to get - when I get ashore I said, I'm going to get away some road. Well I got away - me and him got away and - I - I said where do you live? He says Glasgow. Said, we get there he says, mother'll see us all right. Well anyway we gets t
h
ere and - as soon as his mother saw him she got - go - summonsed the Police. And I flew and I got away you see. But I told - funny thing, I told him that there's a pit there at Borness. I said I'll try there. I said, if I'm going to for to try and get a j
ob in the pit you see.
